A part of my beaut career was spent bringing luxury-esque beauty products to the masses at affordable price points. As a beauty product developer, this was always a unique challenge that I enjoyed, especially working with global manufacturers and suppliers. For me, a brand like @Milani was always one I watched. What I really admire about them is their ability to bring quality formulas from global manufacturers at these affordable prices. One of the ways they do this by focusing their cost of goods on formula, and less on the packaging. People don’t realize that a lot of the times when we are purchasing luxury beauty products, packaging is a huge cost factor. As much as I love my luxury products (I’m a prestige girl at heart) I absolutely LOVE sharing ways to make beauty more accessible for every price point. I’ve found Milani’s products to be highly highly competitive, especially their baked series, tubing mascara, and cream blush being some of my personal Milani favs that are worth checking out. I also don’t mind the packaging, and prefer clear shade windows for products like cream blushes or baked powders. How do y’all feel about Milani? To make imoyo  Passata || fresh tomato  Aromatic (onion,ginger,garlic & scotch bonnet) Palm oil || you can mix with vegetable oil  Salmon || any fish would work  Latifah spice  Seasoning tt Salt tt Water to adjust consistency to preference.  Add aromatic to oil to fry for 2 minutes then go in with passata or fresh tomato, stir and cover to cook for 10 minutes. Add seasonings,spice, stir and go in with the salmon, cook on medium heat for 12-15 minutes.  ************************************************* To make ewedu Ewedu leaves  Locust beans || iru Potash || just enough  Seasoning tt Just enough water  In a saucepan with water add everything except seasoning and bring to a boil for 2 minutes. Pulse couple of times then add seasoning and further cook for 7 minutes.  ************************************************* To make amala Mix water with yam flour.  Add water according to the texture you going for. When it has solidified, add a bit more water cover and allow to steam on very low heat for 13  minutes.
